---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import MadeByKaj from '../../../components/MadeByKaj.astro';

const basePath = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout
	title="The radio bubble | Learn | Found in Space"
	description="How far have Earth's radio signals travelled? Fly outside humanity's electromagnetic footprint and see how small it really is."
>
	<SiteHeader section="Learn" />

	<main class="page">
		<!-- ── Intro ───────────────────────────────── -->

		<section class="intro">
			<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
				<a href={`${basePath}learn/`}>Learn</a>
				<span class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</span>
				<span>The radio bubble</span>
			</nav>
			<p class="eyebrow">Learn</p>
			<h1>The radio bubble</h1>
			<p class="lede">
				In summer 1895, Guglielmo Marconi took wireless telegraphy outdoors at Villa
				Griffone near Bologna. Those electromagnetic waves have been expanding outward
				at the speed of light ever since — a growing sphere centred on Earth. It sounds
				impressive. It is not.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="body-section prose">
			<h2>A sphere of signal</h2>
			<p>
				Every radio broadcast, every television transmission, every radar pulse ever emitted
				by humanity is still out there, propagating through space at 300,000 kilometres per
				second. Using 1 July 1895 as an approximate marker for Marconi's outdoor tests, the
				wavefront has reached a radius of about
				<span data-radio-bubble-radius-ly>131</span> light-years — roughly
				<span data-radio-bubble-radius-pc>40</span> parsecs.
			</p>
			<p>
				That sphere, sometimes called the <em>radio bubble</em>, defines the volume of space
				in which an extraterrestrial civilisation could, in principle, have detected our
				presence. Every star inside the bubble has been washed over by our signals. Every star
				outside it has no electromagnetic evidence that we exist.
			</p>
			<p>
				Scroll through the tour below to see the bubble begin, grow, and reach toward the
				nearest star cluster just beyond its edge.
			</p>
		</section>

		<!-- ── Tour zone ──────────────────────────── -->

		<div class="narrated-tour" data-radio-bubble-tour>
			<div class="narrated-tour__chapters">
				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-viewpoint="before-radio">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Earth orbit · before radio</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Before the bubble</h2>
					<p>
						Before wireless telegraphy, there is no radio bubble. From Earth, the stars
						look exactly as they always did: distant, quiet, and unaware of us. At this
						scale, Earth and the Sun share the same point — the solar origin.
					</p>
					<p>
						Nothing has crossed interstellar space yet. No broadcast, no radar pulse,
						no carrier wave. The story begins with a signal too local to matter to the
						stars — until time gives it distance.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-viewpoint="marconi">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Summer 1895 · Villa Griffone</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Marconi starts the clock</h2>
					<p>
						<strong>Summer 1895 — Marconi’s outdoor wireless telegraphy experiments,
						Villa Griffone, Pontecchio, Italy.</strong> The historical record does not
						give us a precise day, so the tour uses 1 July 1895 as an approximate
						calculation marker.
					</p>
					<p>
						As the chapter begins, the shell grows from Earth at light speed. The camera
						rides just outside the wavefront, turning a century of radio history into a
						few seconds of motion. By the time it settles, the radio bubble has reached
						its present radius.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-viewpoint="outside">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">175 pc from the Sun · outside the shell</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Seeing the shell</h2>
					<p>
						Pull much farther back and the bubble becomes visible as a small, faint
						sphere centred on the Sun, threaded through the local stars. At about
						<span data-radio-bubble-radius-pc>40</span> parsecs radius, it contains
						roughly a thousand stellar systems. That sounds like a lot until you compare
						it with the Milky Way.
					</p>
					<p>
						The galaxy is about 30,000 parsecs across. An
						<span data-radio-bubble-diameter-pc>80</span>-parsec-wide radio bubble is
						large enough to matter locally, but tiny on a galactic scale. From this
						distance, it starts to feel less like a frontier and more like a small
						neighbourhood around one ordinary star.
					</p>
					<p>
						And the signals themselves are weakening. Broadcast-strength radio waves
						follow the inverse-square law: double the distance, quarter the power.
						At <span data-radio-bubble-radius-pc>40</span> parsecs, an ordinary
						television broadcast is billions of times too faint to detect with any
						technology we currently possess. Only a civilisation with an extraordinarily
						sensitive receiver — or one specifically pointed at us — would notice.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-viewpoint="hyades">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">~48 pc from the Sun · just outside the bubble</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">The Hyades: almost in reach</h2>
					<p>
						The Hyades — the nearest open star cluster to the Sun — sit at about
						48 parsecs. That puts them just outside the radio bubble. Our earliest
						signals are roughly <span data-radio-bubble-hyades-gap-pc>8</span> parsecs
						short. At the speed of light, they will arrive in about
						<span data-radio-bubble-hyades-arrival-years>25</span> years.
					</p>
					<p>
						Could anything be listening? The Hyades are about 680 million years old —
						old enough for planets to have formed, settled into stable orbits, and
						cooled. On Earth, life appeared within the first billion years. Microbial
						life at Hyades-age is not impossible, though it would be speculative.
						Complex multicellular life, by Earth's timeline, took over three billion
						years longer.
					</p>
					<p>
						Several Hyades stars have confirmed exoplanets, though the ones found so far
						are hot Jupiters — gas giants in close orbits, unlikely to be habitable. The
						cluster's age means its most massive stars have already died; what remains
						are Sun-like stars and cooler dwarfs. Whether any of them host rocky planets
						in temperate orbits is still unknown.
					</p>
					<p>
						The honest answer: we do not know if anything in the Hyades could hear us.
						But the fact that our signals will reach a real star cluster within a human
						lifetime makes the radio bubble feel less abstract and more like a question
						with a deadline.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-viewpoint="home">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Return · 0 pc</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Back inside</h2>
					<p>
						The journey back from the Hyades is short — only 48 parsecs. Watch the
						bubble's shell pass over you as you re-enter the volume of space that
						knows we are here.
					</p>
					<p>
						From inside, the bubble is invisible again. That is perhaps the most
						sobering part: we cannot see our own signal, and neither can most of the
						galaxy.
					</p>
				</section>

				<div class="narrated-tour__spacer" aria-hidden="true"></div>
			</div>

			<div class="narrated-tour__viewer-col">
				<div class="narrated-tour__viewer-sticky">
					<div class="narrated-tour__nav">
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-viewpoint-fly="before-radio">Before</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-viewpoint-fly="marconi">Marconi</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-viewpoint-fly="outside">Outside</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-viewpoint-fly="hyades">Hyades</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-viewpoint-fly="home">Home</button>
					</div>
					<div class="radio-bubble-viewer-frame">
						<div class="narrated-tour__viewer-shell" data-radio-bubble-shell></div>
						<span
							class="radio-bubble-timeline"
							data-radio-bubble-timeline
							aria-live="off"
							hidden
						></span>
					</div>
					<span class="narrated-tour__status" data-radio-bubble-status>Loading…</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<!-- ── Exploration ideas ──────────────────── -->

		<section class="explore-section">
			<h2>Things to try</h2>
			<div class="explore-grid">
				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Notice</p>
					<h3>The bubble is tiny</h3>
					<p>
						From outside, the radio bubble is barely visible against the stellar
						background. Fly further out and it disappears entirely. Our electromagnetic
						footprint is vanishingly small on a galactic scale.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Try this</p>
					<h3>Count the stars inside</h3>
					<p>
						From outside the bubble, look at how many stars the shell contains. There are
						roughly a thousand stellar systems inside — a tiny fraction of the Milky Way's
						hundreds of billions.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Think about</p>
					<h3>Signal vs. detectability</h3>
					<p>
						The bubble shows where our signals have reached, not where they could be
						detected. Broadcast-power radio fades with the square of distance. Even
						inside the bubble, most signals are far too faint for any plausible receiver.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Key idea</p>
					<h3>Light-speed is the hard limit</h3>
					<p>
						The bubble expands at exactly one light-year per year. Nothing we do can
						make it grow faster. This is not an engineering problem — it is a law of
						physics.
					</p>
				</article>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- ── Closing note ────────────────────────── -->

		<section class="closing-note">
			<div class="panel panel--accent">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Next lesson</p>
				<h3>Explore the clusters themselves</h3>
				<p>
					The Hyades are just one of many star clusters within a few hundred parsecs.
					The <a href={`${basePath}learn/topic/star-clusters/`} class="link--gold">star clusters lesson</a>
					flies between five clusters — from stellar nurseries to ancient globulars — to
					see how age, gravity, and the galaxy shape stellar families.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<MadeByKaj />
	</main>
</Layout>

<script>
	import { mountRadioBubbleViewer } from '../../../scripts/radio-bubble-viewer.js';
	import { setupNarratedTour } from '../../../scripts/narrated-tour.js';

	const tourRoot = document.querySelector('[data-radio-bubble-tour]');
	const mount = document.querySelector('[data-radio-bubble-shell]');
	const statusEl = document.querySelector('[data-radio-bubble-status]');
	const timelineEl = document.querySelector('[data-radio-bubble-timeline]');
	const chapters = tourRoot?.querySelectorAll('.narrated-tour__chapter[data-viewpoint]') ?? [];
	const navButtons = tourRoot?.querySelectorAll('[data-viewpoint-fly]') ?? [];
	const HYADES_DISTANCE_PC = Math.hypot(17.574, 42.316, 13.963);
	const LY_PER_PC = 3.2615637775591093;
	const JULIAN_YEAR_MS = 365.25 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000;
	const FIRST_RADIO_SIGNAL_DATE_UTC_MS = Date.UTC(1895, 6, 1);

	if (mount && tourRoot) {
		mountRadioBubbleViewer(mount, {
			onStatus(msg) {
				if (statusEl) statusEl.textContent = msg;
			},
			onTimelineDateChange(label) {
				if (!timelineEl) return;
				if (label) {
					timelineEl.textContent = label;
					timelineEl.hidden = false;
					return;
				}
				timelineEl.textContent = '';
				timelineEl.hidden = true;
			},
		}).then((result) => {
			updateComputedCopy(result);
			window.setInterval(() => updateComputedCopy(result), 1000);
			setupNarratedTour({
				root: tourRoot,
				chapters,
				navButtons,
				getChapterId(chapter) {
					return chapter.dataset.viewpoint;
				},
				getNavButtonId(button) {
					return button.dataset.viewpointFly;
				},
				activate(id) {
					result.goTo(id);
				},
				statusEl,
				initialId: 'before-radio',
			});
		}).catch((err) => {
			console.error('[website:radio-bubble]', err);
			if (statusEl) statusEl.textContent = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);
		});
	}

	function updateComputedCopy(result) {
		const liveRadiusLy = Math.max(
			0,
			(Date.now() - FIRST_RADIO_SIGNAL_DATE_UTC_MS) / JULIAN_YEAR_MS,
		);
		const radiusLy = liveRadiusLy || Math.max(0, Number(result.radiusLy) || 0);
		const radiusPc = radiusLy / LY_PER_PC;
		const hyadesGapPc = Math.max(0, HYADES_DISTANCE_PC - radiusPc);

		setCopyValue('[data-radio-bubble-radius-ly]', formatWholeNumber(radiusLy));
		setCopyValue('[data-radio-bubble-radius-pc]', formatWholeNumber(radiusPc));
		setCopyValue('[data-radio-bubble-diameter-pc]', formatWholeNumber(radiusPc * 2));
		setCopyValue('[data-radio-bubble-hyades-gap-pc]', formatWholeNumber(hyadesGapPc));
		setCopyValue(
			'[data-radio-bubble-hyades-arrival-years]',
			formatPreciseYears(hyadesGapPc * LY_PER_PC),
		);
	}

	function setCopyValue(selector, value) {
		document.querySelectorAll(selector).forEach((el) => {
			el.textContent = value;
		});
	}

	function formatWholeNumber(value) {
		return String(Math.max(0, Math.round(Number(value) || 0)));
	}

	function formatPreciseYears(value) {
		return Math.max(0, Number(value) || 0).toFixed(6);
	}
</script>

<style>
	/* ── Page ──────────────────────────────────────── */

	.page {
		position: relative;
		min-height: 100vh;
		padding-top: 3.5rem;
	}

	/* ── Intro ─────────────────────────────────────── */

	.intro {
		max-width: 48rem;
		padding: 2rem 0 0;
	}

	h1,
	h2,
	h3 {
		margin: 0;
		font-weight: 600;
		letter-spacing: -0.03em;
	}

	h1 {
		font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 4.2rem);
		line-height: 1.02;
		max-width: 18ch;
	}

	h2 {
		font-size: 1.55rem;
		line-height: 1.1;
		margin-bottom: 0.85rem;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	h3 {
		font-size: 1.3rem;
		line-height: 1.15;
		margin-bottom: 0.65rem;
	}

	p {
		margin: 0;
		line-height: 1.75;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	p + p {
		margin-top: 1rem;
	}

	/* ── Body text ─────────────────────────────────── */

	.body-section {
		max-width: 48rem;
		padding: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
	}

	/* ── Viewer overlay ───────────────────────────── */

	.radio-bubble-viewer-frame {
		position: relative;
	}

	.radio-bubble-timeline {
		position: absolute;
		top: 0.75rem;
		right: 0.75rem;
		z-index: 2;
		padding: 0.28rem 0.62rem;
		border: 1px solid rgba(141, 183, 255, 0.28);
		border-radius: 999px;
		background: rgba(2, 4, 11, 0.72);
		box-shadow: 0 10px 30px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.28);
		color: var(--fis-text);
		font-size: 0.82rem;
		font-weight: 600;
		line-height: 1.15;
		letter-spacing: 0;
		pointer-events: none;
		backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
	}

	.radio-bubble-timeline[hidden] {
		display: none;
	}

	/* ── Explore section ──────────────────────────── */

	.explore-section {
		max-width: 48rem;
		padding: 1rem 0 0;
	}

	.explore-grid {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
		gap: 1rem;
		margin-top: 1.5rem;
		margin-bottom: 2rem;
	}

	.explore-grid h3 {
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	.explore-grid p {
		font-size: 0.96rem;
		line-height: 1.7;
	}

	/* ── Closing note ─────────────────────────────── */

	.closing-note {
		max-width: 48rem;
		margin-bottom: 2rem;
	}

	.closing-note h3 {
		margin: 0 0 0.65rem;
		font-size: 1.4rem;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	.closing-note p {
		line-height: 1.75;
	}

	/* ── Responsive ───────────────────────────────── */

	@media (max-width: 960px) {
		.explore-grid {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		}
	}

	@media (max-width: 720px) {
		.page {
			padding-top: 2.2rem;
		}

		h1 {
			font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 12vw, 3.6rem);
		}

		.radio-bubble-timeline {
			top: 0.55rem;
			right: 0.55rem;
			padding: 0.24rem 0.52rem;
			font-size: 0.76rem;
		}
	}
</style>
